				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Playing freely up and down the fingerboard and been able to visualise your available notes within any given key can be a real challenge - especially for bass players, as a lot of the time we're playing the <em>money notes</em> in the lower register of the instrument, i.e. the notes we get payed to play! ;) This means that when we venture up into the higher register of the fingerboard, things can get scary - fast!</p>
<p>In this lesson I'm going to show you a great way to start visualizing your scales upon the fingerboard - in a way that organizes everything into 3 easy to learn patterns, and once learned can be linked up into multiple combinations to achieve total freedom when playing over the entire fingerboard.</p>
<p>As always, see you in the shed...</p>
<p>Scott :)</p>
</p>
<p>PS. If you enjoy this lesson and <em>really</em> want to become a "scales/arpeggios &amp; chord tones ninja" on the bass you should check out our new 10+ hour course, <a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/harmonic-layering-arpeggios-chord-tones-scales" target="_blank">"<em>Harmonic Layering - A Comprehensive Guide To Chord Tones, Arpeggios &amp; Scales"</em></a>.</p>
<p>Within the new course I cover arpeggios, chord tones, scales, pentatonic scales, the modes, uses of more exotic scales, but most importantly - I show you how to use all of these elements to create awesome bass lines, grooves and solos!</p>
<p>​In other words - I not only show you everything I know, I also show you how to actually use this information in <em>real life situations</em>!</p>
